{"title_page": "Coliseum Theatre (Washington Heights)", "text_new": "{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = Coliseum Theatre\n| image              = Coliseum Cinemas 701 W 181st St jeh.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption            = Coliseum Theatre in 2013 \n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 4260 Broadway\n| city               = New York City\n| country            = United States\n| designation        = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|40.850451|-73.935275|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=ti}}\n| architect          = [[Eugene De Rosa]] <br> Percival Raymond Pereira\n| builder            = Fleischmann Construction<ref name=\"mcny\">https://collections.mcny.org/Collection/B.-S.-Moss-Coliseum-Theatre-2F3XC5XLGPQ.html</ref>\n| owner              = The Greater New York Vaudeville Theatre Corp<ref name=\"mcny\"/>\n| tenant             = \n| operator           = \n| capacity           = 3,500\n| type               = Theatre\n| opened             = September 30, 1920\n| reopened           = \n| yearsactive        = 1920\u20132002<br>2004-2011\n| rebuilt            = \n| closed             = 2011\n| demolished         = \n| othernames         = B.S. Moss' Coliseum Theatre <br> New Coliseum Theatre <br> Coliseum Cinemas\n| production         = \n| currentuse         = Vacant\n| website            = \n}}\n\nThe Coliseum Theatre is a vacant cultural and performing arts center located at 4260 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] between West 181st and 182nd Streets in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. A full-block building, it is bounded on the east by Bennett Avenue.\n\nDuring the [[American Revolution]], it was the location of the Blue Bell Tavern, which stood from 1720 to right before the Coliseum was erected, in 1915.<ref>http://www.washington-heights.us/rko-coliseum-theater/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nypl.org/blog/2012/01/13/ghost-light-illuminating-our-citys-theatres-rko-coliseum-edition|title=Ghost Light: Illuminating Our City's Theatres: RKO Coliseum|publisher=The New York Publuc Library|author=Jeremy Megraw|date=January 13, 2012|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBuilt in 1920 as B.S. Moss' Coliseum Theatre, the venue was originally a movie palace designed by architect [[Eugene De Rosa]]. <ref name=\"cinema\"/> Marble interiors were done by Voska, Foelsch, & Sidlo Inc, terra cotta by New York Architectural Terra Cotta Company, ornamental plastering by Architectural Plastering Company, Inc., Peter Clark installed the rigging system, windows supplied by S. H. Pomeroy Company, Inc., Sexauer & Lemke Inc. installed the ornamental iron work, draperies and wall coverings by Louis Kuhn Studio, mirrors & console tables by Nonnenbacher & Co, and the pipe organ was installed by [[M. P. Moller]]<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy_nAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR53&lpg=RA1-PR53&dq=coliseum+theatre+washington+heights&source=bl&ots=60oVy-asfo&sig=ACfU3U0-9xxTRIwaUrrdhAAiNVHz0YptmA&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjhjqeq3_rkAhWBT98KHUxYCSk4MhDoATAFegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=coliseum%20theatre%20washington%20heights&f=false</ref>\n\nThe Coliseum was launched by [[Bow Tie Cinemas]] before being taken over by [[RKO Pictures]]. It housed many [[vaudeville]] acts, including [[The Marx Brothers]], [[ W.C. Fields]], [[Eddie Cantor]], Uncle Don\u2019s Kiddie Show, and [[Gertrude Berg]].<ref name=\"cinema\">http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/526</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, a local arts group wanted to rejuvenate the Coliseum as a community arts center, and put on a fundraiser benefit performance ''Salute to Ol' Vaudeville''. It also was the site of the Dominican Film Festival and Children's Film Festival before closing.<ref name=\"ghost\"/>\n\nIn 2011, the building was denied larkmark status, and a shopping mall is slated to be opened after demolition.<ref>https://www.crainsnewyork.com/features/old-movie-theaters-are-hoping-hollywood-ending</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\"  widths=\"250px\" heights=\"250px\" caption=\"Gallery\">\nFile:Auditorium from stage, Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre Washington Heights 4261 Broadway.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre Washington Heights east facade detail.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre Washington Heights south facade detail.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\nFile:Entrance to upper foyer, Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\nFile:Interior, side view, Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpeg\nFile:Lobby of Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1920 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Cinemas and movie theaters in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Former theatres in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Movie palaces]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Theatres completed in 1920]]\n[[Category:Washington Heights, Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = Coliseum Theatre\n| image              = Coliseum Cinemas 701 W 181st St jeh.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption            = Coliseum Theatre in 2013 \n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 4260 Broadway\n| city               = New York City\n| country            = United States\n| designation        = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|40.850451|-73.935275|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=ti}}\n| architect          = [[Eugene De Rosa]] <br> Percival Raymond Pereira\n| builder            = Fleischmann Construction<ref name=\"mcny\">https://collections.mcny.org/Collection/B.-S.-Moss-Coliseum-Theatre-2F3XC5XLGPQ.html</ref>\n| owner              = The Greater New York Vaudeville Theatre Corp<ref name=\"mcny\"/>\n| tenant             = \n| operator           = \n| capacity           = 3,500\n| type               = Theatre\n| opened             = September 30, 1920\n| reopened           = \n| yearsactive        = 1920\u20132002<br>2004-2011\n| rebuilt            = \n| closed             = 2011\n| demolished         = \n| othernames         = B.S. Moss' Coliseum Theatre <br> New Coliseum Theatre <br> Coliseum Cinemas\n| production         = \n| currentuse         = Vacant\n| website            = \n}}\n\nThe Coliseum Theatre is a vacant cultural and performing arts center located at 4260 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] between West 181st and 182nd Streets in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. A full-block building, it is bounded on the east by Bennett Avenue.\n\nDuring the [[American Revolution]], it was the location of the Blue Bell Tavern, which stood from 1720 to right before the Coliseum was erected, in 1915.<ref>http://www.washington-heights.us/rko-coliseum-theater/</ref><ref name=\"ghost\">https://www.nypl.org/blog/2012/01/13/ghost-light-illuminating-our-citys-theatres-rko-coliseum-edition</ref>\n\nBuilt in 1920 as B.S. Moss' Coliseum Theatre, the venue was originally a movie palace designed by architect [[Eugene De Rosa]]. <ref name=\"cinema\"/> Marble interiors were done by Voska, Foelsch, & Sidlo Inc, terra cotta by New York Architectural Terra Cotta Company, ornamental plastering by Architectural Plastering Company, Inc., Peter Clark installed the rigging system, windows supplied by S. H. Pomeroy Company, Inc., Sexauer & Lemke Inc. installed the ornamental iron work, draperies and wall coverings by Louis Kuhn Studio, mirrors & console tables by Nonnenbacher & Co, and the pipe organ was installed by [[M. P. Moller]]<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy_nAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR53&lpg=RA1-PR53&dq=coliseum+theatre+washington+heights&source=bl&ots=60oVy-asfo&sig=ACfU3U0-9xxTRIwaUrrdhAAiNVHz0YptmA&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjhjqeq3_rkAhWBT98KHUxYCSk4MhDoATAFegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=coliseum%20theatre%20washington%20heights&f=false</ref>\n\nThe Coliseum was launched by [[Bow Tie Cinemas]] before being taken over by [[RKO Pictures]]. It housed many [[vaudeville]] acts, including [[The Marx Brothers]], [[ W.C. Fields]], [[Eddie Cantor]], Uncle Don\u2019s Kiddie Show, and [[Gertrude Berg]].<ref name=\"cinema\">http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/526</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, a local arts group wanted to rejuvenate the Coliseum as a community arts center, and put on a fundraiser benefit performance ''Salute to Ol' Vaudeville''. It also was the site of the Dominican Film Festival and Children's Film Festival before closing.<ref name=\"ghost\"/>\n\nIn 2011, the building was denied larkmark status, and a shopping mall is slated to be opened after demoltion.<ref>https://www.crainsnewyork.com/features/old-movie-theaters-are-hoping-hollywood-ending</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\"  widths=\"250px\" heights=\"250px\" caption=\"Gallery\">\nFile:Auditorium from stage, Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre Washington Heights 4261 Broadway.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre Washington Heights east facade detail.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre Washington Heights south facade detail.jpg\nFile:Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\nFile:Entrance to upper foyer, Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\nFile:Interior, side view, Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpeg\nFile:Lobby of Coliseum Theatre, 181st Street.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1920 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Cinemas and movie theaters in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Former theatres in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Movie palaces]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Theatres completed in 1920]]\n[[Category:Washington Heights, Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "The Spirit of Oohoowahoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "improved citation & fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coliseum_Theatre_(Washington_Heights)"}
{"title_page": "Windows-1252", "text_new": "{{Short description|Code page used for the Latin alphabets of Western European languages}}\n{{About|the character encoding commonly mislabeled as \"ANSI\"|the actual ANSI character encoding|ASCII|the actual \"ANSI extended Latin\" encoding|ANSEL}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox character encoding\n| name     = Windows-1252\n| mime     = windows-1252\n| image    = Windows-1252-infobox.svg\n| caption  = \n| alias    = \n| by       = [[Microsoft]]\n| standard = WHATWG Encoding Standard\n| lang     = [[English language|English]], [[Western Latin character sets (computing)|various others]]\n| status   =\n| extends  = [[ISO 8859-1]] (excluding C1 controls)\n| prev     = \n| next     = \n| encodes  = [[ISO 8859-15]]\n| classification = [[extended ASCII]], [[Windows-125x]]\n}}\n\n'''Windows-1252''' or '''CP-1252''' ([[code page]] 1252) is a single-byte [[character encoding]] of the [[Latin alphabet]], used by default in the [[legacy system|legacy]] components of [[Microsoft Windows]] for English and some other Western languages (other languages use different default encodings).\n\n{{As of|2020|04}}, 0.4% of all web sites declared use of Windows-1252,<ref name=\"encoding\">{{cite web|url=https://w3techs.com/technologies/history_overview/character_encoding|title=Historical trends in the usage of character encodings, March 2020|publisher=|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://w3techs.com/faq|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=}}</ref> but at the same time 2.3% used [[ISO/IEC 8859-1|ISO&nbsp;8859-1]] (0.7% of top-1000 websites),<ref name=\"encoding\"/> which by HTML5 standards should be considered the same encoding,<ref name=\"WHATWG\" /> so that 2.7% of web sites effectively use Windows-1252.\n\n==Details==\nThis character encoding is a [[superset]] of [[ISO/IEC 8859-1|ISO&nbsp;8859-1]] in terms of printable characters, but differs from the IANA's ISO-8859-1 by using displayable characters rather than control characters in the 80 to 9F ([[hexadecimal|hex]]) range. Notable additional characters include [[quotation mark|curly quotation marks]] and all the printable characters that are in [[ISO/IEC 8859-15|ISO&nbsp;8859-15]] (at different places than ISO&nbsp;8859-15). It is known to Windows by the [[Windows code page|code page]] number 1252, and by the [[Internet Assigned Numbers Authority|IANA]]-approved name \"windows-1252\".\n\n<!-- I think the following text is right but I need to do some checking first before I uncomment it (not quite true, yes it happened, but Netscape, Mosaic, et al. were at fault as well :)\nAt one stage many MS internet products produced text in Windows-1252 but marked as ISO-8859-1. This has resulted in other internet applications treating ISO-8859-1 as meaning Windows-1252 to maintain compatibility with Microsoft products.\nFollowing text is copied (mostly) from ISO-8859-1 page.\n-->It is very common to mislabel Windows-1252 text with the charset label ISO-8859-1. A common result was that all the quotes and apostrophes (produced by \"smart quotes\" in word-processing software) were replaced with question marks or boxes on non-Windows operating systems, making text difficult to read. Most modern web browsers and e-mail clients treat the [[media type]] charset ISO-8859-1 as Windows-1252 to accommodate such mislabeling. This is now standard behavior in the [[HTML5 in mobile devices|HTML5]] specification, which requires that documents advertised as ISO-8859-1 actually be parsed with the Windows-1252 encoding.<ref name=\"WHATWG\">{{cite web |url=https://encoding.spec.whatwg.org/#names-and-labels |title=Encoding |at=sec. 5.2 Names and labels |publisher=[[WHATWG]] |date=27 January 2015 |accessdate=4 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204174315/https://encoding.spec.whatwg.org/#names-and-labels |archivedate=4 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><!-- No authors listed on page, but GitHub lists contributors as -->\n\nHistorically, the phrase \"ANSI Code Page\" was used in Windows to refer to non-DOS encodings; the intention was that most of these would be [[ANSI]] standards such as [[ISO-8859-1]]. Even though Windows-1252 was the first and by far most popular code page named so in Microsoft Windows parlance, the code page has never been an ANSI standard. Microsoft explains, \"The term ANSI as used to signify Windows code pages is a historical reference, but is nowadays a misnomer that continues to persist in the Windows community.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://download.microsoft.com/download/5/6/8/56803da0-e4a0-4796-a62c-ca920b73bb17/21-Unicode_WinXP.pdf |title=Unicode and Windows XP |page=1 |last1=Wissink |first1=Cathy |publisher=[[Microsoft]] |date=5 April 2002 |accessdate=4 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204175931/http://download.microsoft.com/download/5/6/8/56803da0-e4a0-4796-a62c-ca920b73bb17/21-Unicode_WinXP.pdf |archivedate=4 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn [[LaTeX]] packages, CP-1252 is referred to as \"ansinew\".\n\n{{anchor|Code page layout}}\n\n==Character set==\nThe following table shows Windows-1252. Each character is shown with its [[Unicode]] equivalent based on the Unicode.org mapping of Windows-1252 with \"best fit\".<ref name=bestfit>{{cite web |url=https://www.unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MICSFT/WindowsBestFit/bestfit1252.txt |title=Unicode mappings of Windows-1252 with 'Best Fit' |publisher=[[Unicode]] |accessdate=4 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204175922/http://www.unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MICSFT/WindowsBestFit/bestfit1252.txt |archivedate=4 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| {{chset-tableformat}}\n{{chset-table-header|Windows-1252 (CP1252)}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|0_<br/>0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0000|[[Null character|NUL]]|0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0001|[[Start of heading|SOH]]|1}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0002|[[Start of text|STX]]|2}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0003|[[End of text|ETX]]|3}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0004|[[End of transmission character|EOT]]|4}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0005|[[Enquiry character|ENQ]]|5}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0006|[[Acknowledge character|ACK]]|6}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0007|[[Bell character|BEL]]|7}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0008|[[Backspace|BS]]|8}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0009|[[Tab character|HT]]|9}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|000A|[[Line feed|LF]]|10}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|000B|[[Vertical tab|VT]]|11}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|000C|[[Form feed|FF]]|12}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|000D|[[Carriage return|CR]]|13}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|000E|[[Shift out|SO]]|14}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|000F|[[Shift in|SI]]|15}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|1_<br/>16}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0010|[[Data link escape|DLE]]|16}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0011|[[Device Control 1|DC1]]|17}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0012|[[Device Control 2|DC2]]|18}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0013|[[Device Control 3|DC3]]|19}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0014|[[Device Control 4|DC4]]|20}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0015|[[Negative acknowledge character|NAK]]|21}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0016|[[Synchronous idle|SYN]]|22}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0017|[[End of transmission block|ETB]]|23}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0018|[[Cancel character|CAN]]|24}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0019|[[End of medium|EM]]|25}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|001A|[[Substitute character|SUB]]|26}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|001B|[[Escape character|ESC]]|27}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|001C|[[File separator|FS]]|28}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|001D|[[Group separator|GS]]|29}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-