ceived by Rosario Dawson|Awards for Rosario Dawson]]\n|list =\n{{NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Motion Picture}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Supporting Actress Motion Picture}}\n{{Streamy Awards Acting Performance Winners}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dawson, Rosario}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American entertainers of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American video game actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American women philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:People of Afro-Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Squatters]]\n[[Category:Streamy Award winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n", "name_user": "Brainulator9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosario_Dawson"}
{"title_page": "J. J. Isler", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = J. J. Isler\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| fullname    = Jennifer J. Isler\n| birth_name  = Jennifer J. Fetter\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1963|12|01}}\n| birth_place = [[La Jolla, San Diego|La Jolla]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| occupation  = Yachtswoman\n| known_for   = Olympic and America's Cup sailor\n| headercolor = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|sailing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalOlympics}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Sailing at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 470|470 class]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Barcelona]] | [[Sailing at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 470|470 class]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Jennifer J. Isler''' (born December 1, 1963), best known as '''J. J. Isler''' and also known by her maiden name of '''J. J. Fetter''', is an American [[sailor|yachtswoman]]. She is a two-time Olympic medalist and a world sailing champion. She was a starting helmsman in the [[1995 America's Cup]] races. A pioneer in the sport of women's sailing, she was the first woman inducted into the Sailing World Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"SW\">[http://www.sailingworld.com/racing/sw-hall-of-fame/jj-isler-37443.html Sailing World]</ref>\n\nShe was born into a sailing family, the youngest of three children of Jane and Tom Fetter; he is a former commodore of the [[San Diego Yacht Club]].<ref name=\"People\">[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105132,00.html People, February 20, 1995]</ref> She began sailing [[Sabot (dinghy)|Sabots]] when she was 7 years old.<ref>[http://www.sdhoc.com/newswire/2010-breitbard-hall-of-famer-jj-fetter-isler/ San Diego Hall of Champions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302204126/http://www.sdhoc.com/newswire/2010-breitbard-hall-of-famer-jj-fetter-isler |date=2012-03-02 }}</ref> She learned to sail and race in the Juniors program at the San Diego Yacht Club, sailing mostly in Sabots. An intense competitor, she disliked the fact that girls and boys were viewed differently in sailing. \"The junior regattas were open to everyone, but there was a winner's trophy and a 'first girls' trophy,\" she recalled recently. \"I always wanted just to be first, and hand that other trophy off as 'the first boy trophy'. \u2026 I finished second, third and fourth in the Sabot Nationals, but never won, meaning I was always getting that 'first girl' trophy, and I hated it.\"<ref name=\"UT\">[http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/feb/22/sailor-blazed-trail-for-women/ San Diego Union Tribune, February 22, 2010]</ref> At the time, many of the West Coast's leading yacht clubs didn't even have facilities for female sailors. She once had to dress for a race in a yacht's club's parking lot.<ref name=\"UT\" />\n\nHer horizons expanded in high school, when she started racing boats other than Sabots, particularly [[420 (dinghy)|420s]]. She was recruited by several colleges, and chose [[Yale]] because they promised her she could compete on the varsity team, not just the women's team. At Yale she was the first woman captain of the sailing team.<ref name=\"People\" /> She became only the third female sailor in the history of intercollegiate sailing to be named an All American.<ref name=\"UT\" />\n\nShe went on to win medals in the National, European, and World championships in 1987\u20131988 in the women's [[470 (dinghy)|470s]].<ref name=\"UT\" /> She won the World Championship in 1991. She also won the Rolex International Women's Keelboat Championship in 1986.<ref name=\"SW\" /> She has been named the Rolex Yachtswoman of the Year four times.<ref>[http://www.ussailing.org/awards/rolex/ Rolex Yachtswoman of the year] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715230403/http://www.ussailing.org/awards/rolex/ |date=2010-07-15 }}</ref>\n\nShe won a bronze medal at the [[Sailing at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Summer Olympics]] and a silver medal in the [[Sailing at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Summer Olympics]], skippering in the women's [[470 (dinghy)|470 class]].<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/is/jj-isler-1.html |title=JJ Isler (full name: Jennifer J. Fetter Isler)}}</ref>\n\nShe was the starting helmsman and tactician for the all-female Mighty Mary USA-34 team for most of the 1995 America's Cup [[1995 Citizen Cup|defense trial races]], until she was replaced by David Dellenbaugh in a controversial move.<ref name=\"SW\" />\n\nWith her then-husband [[Peter Isler]], another champion sailor, she co-wrote the book ''Sailing for Dummies''.\n\nShe was inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nshof.org/inductees/fetter-jennifer-anne-jj/|title=Jennifer Anne Fetter 2015 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Sailing for Dummies'', by J.J. and Peter Isler, 2nd edition, Wiley Publishing, 2006, {{ISBN|978-0471791430}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{World Sailing profile|memberid=57172|id=USAJI3|name=JJ ISLER (nee FETTER)}}\n* [http://www.sailingworld.com/article/Jennifer-JJ-Fetter-Isler Interview] when named to the Sailing World Hall of Fame\n\n{{Footer World Champions Women's 470}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isler, J. J.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American female sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:1995 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 470]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 470]]\n[[Category:Yale Bulldogs sailors]]\n[[Category:470 class world champions]]\n[[Category:People from La Jolla, San Diego]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:US Sailor of the Year]]\n[[Category:World champions in sailing for the United States of America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = J. J. Isler\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| fullname    = Jennifer J. Isler\n| birth_name  = Jennifer J. Fetter\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1963|12|01}}\n| birth_place = [[La Jolla, San Diego|La Jolla]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| occupation  = Yachtswoman\n| known_for   = Olympic and America's Cup sailor\n| headercolor = lightsteelblue\n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|sailing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalOlympics}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Sailing at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 470|470 class]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Barcelona]] | [[Sailing at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 470|470 class]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Jennifer J. Isler''' (born December 1, 1963), best known as '''J. J. Isler''' and also known by her maiden name of '''J. J. Fetter''', is an American [[sailor|yachtswoman]]. She is a two-time Olympic medalist and a world sailing champion. She was a starting helmsman in the [[1995 America's Cup]] races. A pioneer in the sport of women's sailing, she was the first woman inducted into the Sailing World Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"SW\">[http://www.sailingworld.com/racing/sw-hall-of-fame/jj-isler-37443.html Sailing World]</ref>\n\nShe was born into a sailing family, the youngest of three children of Jane and Tom Fetter; he is a former commodore of the [[San Diego Yacht Club]].<ref name=\"People\">[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105132,00.html People, February 20, 1995]</ref> She began sailing [[Sabot (dinghy)|Sabots]] when she was 7 years old.<ref>[http://www.sdhoc.com/newswire/2010-breitbard-hall-of-famer-jj-fetter-isler/ San Diego Hall of Champions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302204126/http://www.sdhoc.com/newswire/2010-breitbard-hall-of-famer-jj-fetter-isler |date=2012-03-02 }}</ref> She learned to sail and race in the Juniors program at the San Diego Yacht Club, sailing mostly in Sabots. An intense competitor, she disliked the fact that girls and boys were viewed differently in sailing. \"The junior regattas were open to everyone, but there was a winner's trophy and a 'first girls' trophy,\" she recalled recently. \"I always wanted just to be first, and hand that other trophy off as 'the first boy trophy'. \u2026 I finished second, third and fourth in the Sabot Nationals, but never won, meaning I was always getting that 'first girl' trophy, and I hated it.\"<ref name=\"UT\">[http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/feb/22/sailor-blazed-trail-for-women/ San Diego Union Tribune, February 22, 2010]</ref> At the time, many of the West Coast's leading yacht clubs didn't even have facilities for female sailors. She once had to dress for a race in a yacht's club's parking lot.<ref name=\"UT\" />\n\nHer horizons expanded in high school, when she started racing boats other than Sabots, particularly [[420 (dinghy)|420s]]. She was recruited by several colleges, and chose [[Yale]] because they promised her she could compete on the varsity team, not just the women's team. At Yale she was the first woman captain of the sailing team.<ref name=\"People\" /> She became only the third female sailor in the history of intercollegiate sailing to be named an All American.<ref name=\"UT\" />\n\nShe went on to win medals in the National, European, and World championships in 1987\u20131988 in the women's [[470 (dinghy)|470s]].<ref name=\"UT\" /> She won the World Championship in 1991. She also won the Rolex International Women's Keelboat Championship in 1986.<ref name=\"SW\" /> She has been named the Rolex Yachtswoman of the Year four times.<ref>[http://www.ussailing.org/awards/rolex/ Rolex Yachtswoman of the year] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715230403/http://www.ussailing.org/awards/rolex/ |date=2010-07-15 }}</ref>\n\nShe won a bronze medal at the [[Sailing at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Summer Olympics]] and a silver medal in the [[Sailing at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Summer Olympics]], skippering in the women's [[470 (dinghy)|470 class]].<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/is/jj-isler-1.html |title=JJ Isler (full name: Jennifer J. Fetter Isler)}}</ref>\n\nShe was the starting helmsman and tactician for the all-female Mighty Mary USA-34 team for most of the 1995 America's Cup [[1995 Citizen Cup|defense trial races]], until she was replaced by David Dellenbaugh in a controversial move.<ref name=\"SW\" />\n\nWith her then-husband [[Peter Isler]], another champion sailor, she co-wrote the book ''Sailing for Dummies''.\n\nShe was inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nshof.org/hall-of-fame/194-the-national-sailing-hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-2015/993-fetter-jennifer-anne-qjjq-2015-hall-of-fame|title=Jennifer Anne Fetter 2015 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=December 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Sailing for Dummies'', by J.J. and Peter Isler, 2nd edition, Wiley Publishing, 2006, {{ISBN|978-0471791430}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{World Sailing profile|memberid=57172|id=USAJI3|name=JJ ISLER (nee FETTER)}}\n* [http://www.sailingworld.com/article/Jennifer-JJ-Fetter-Isler Interview] when named to the Sailing World Hall of Fame\n\n{{Footer World Champions Women's 470}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isler, J. J.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American female sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:1995 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 470]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 470]]\n[[Category:Yale Bulldogs sailors]]\n[[Category:470 class world champions]]\n[[Category:People from La Jolla, San Diego]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:US Sailor of the Year]]\n[[Category:World champions in sailing for the United States of America]]\n", "name_user": "Cajohnson56", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed NSHOF reference link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._J._Isler"}
